# Idea Hub Agent Workflow

The Idea Hub is VibrationFit's internal project management system. Agents can read and write Idea Hub data using the **Supabase MCP** tools (`execute_sql`, `list_tables`).

## Schema Reference

### Core Tables

| Table | Purpose | Key Columns |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `idea_projects` | Top-level project/idea | `id`, `title`, `description`, `category_id`, `status` (idea/planned/in_progress/review/done/archived), `priority` (low/medium/high/urgent), `due_date`, `created_by` |
| `idea_tasks` | Tasks and subtasks within a project | `id`, `project_id`, `parent_task_id` (NULL=top-level, non-NULL=subtask; max 1 level deep), `title`, `description`, `is_complete`, `sort_order` |
| `idea_categories` | Grouping (Feature, Course, Social Media, Marketing, etc.) | `id`, `name`, `color`, `icon` |
| `idea_tags` | Freeform labels | `id`, `name`, `color` |
| `idea_project_tags` | Many-to-many join | `project_id`, `tag_id` |
| `idea_comments` | Activity log and comments | `id`, `project_id`, `user_id`, `body`, `type` (comment/status_change/system), `metadata` |
| `idea_attachments` | File/URL references | `id`, `project_id`, `file_name`, `file_url` |
| `idea_custom_field_defs` | Custom field definitions | `id`, `name`, `field_type` (text/number/date/select/url/boolean), `options`, `category_id` |
| `idea_custom_field_values` | Custom field values per project | `id`, `project_id`, `field_id`, `value` |
| `idea_project_links` | Inter-project relationships | `id`, `source_project_id`, `target_project_id`, `link_type` (related/blocks/blocked_by/parent/child) |

## Read Patterns

### Get a project with its tasks

```sql
SELECT p.id, p.title, p.description, p.status, p.priority
FROM idea_projects p
WHERE p.id = '<project_id>';

SELECT t.id, t.title, t.description, t.is_complete, t.parent_task_id, t.sort_order
FROM idea_tasks t
WHERE t.project_id = '<project_id>'
ORDER BY t.parent_task_id NULLS FIRST, t.sort_order;
```

### Get a specific task with its subtasks

```sql
SELECT t.id, t.title, t.description, t.is_complete, t.parent_task_id
FROM idea_tasks t
WHERE t.id = '<task_id>' OR t.parent_task_id = '<task_id>'
ORDER BY t.parent_task_id NULLS FIRST, t.sort_order;
```

### List all projects with a given status

```sql
SELECT id, title, status, priority, due_date
FROM idea_projects
WHERE status = 'in_progress'
ORDER BY priority DESC, created_at;
```

## Write Patterns

### Mark a task complete

```sql
UPDATE idea_tasks SET is_complete = true WHERE id = '<task_id>';
```

### Add a comment (agent activity log)

```sql
INSERT INTO idea_comments (project_id, body, type)
VALUES ('<project_id>', 'Completed task: <describe what was done>', 'system');
```

### Update project status

```sql
UPDATE idea_projects SET status = 'review' WHERE id = '<project_id>';
```

### Create a subtask

```sql
INSERT INTO idea_tasks (project_id, parent_task_id, title, description, sort_order)
VALUES ('<project_id>', '<parent_task_id>', 'Subtask title', 'Details...', 0);
```

## Agent Workflow Protocol

When an agent is assigned work from the Idea Hub, follow these steps:

### 1. Read context

Query the project description, the assigned task, its subtasks, and any linked projects to understand full scope.

```sql
-- Get project context
SELECT title, description, status FROM idea_projects WHERE id = '<project_id>';

-- Get all tasks for this project (tree structure)
SELECT id, title, description, is_complete, parent_task_id, sort_order
FROM idea_tasks WHERE project_id = '<project_id>'
ORDER BY parent_task_id NULLS FIRST, sort_order;
```

### 2. Do the work

Implement what the task description says. Use the task `description` field for detailed acceptance criteria and instructions.

### 3. Mark task complete

```sql
UPDATE idea_tasks SET is_complete = true WHERE id = '<task_id>';
```

### 4. Add a comment summarizing what was done

```sql
INSERT INTO idea_comments (project_id, body, type)
VALUES ('<project_id>', 'Completed: <brief summary of changes made, files touched>', 'system');
```

### 5. Check parent task completion

If this was a subtask, check if all siblings are done. If so, mark the parent done too.

```sql
-- Check if all subtasks of parent are complete
SELECT COUNT(*) AS remaining
FROM idea_tasks
WHERE parent_task_id = '<parent_task_id>' AND is_complete = false;

-- If remaining = 0, mark parent complete
UPDATE idea_tasks SET is_complete = true WHERE id = '<parent_task_id>';
```

### 6. Check project completion

If all tasks in the project are done, suggest moving the project to `review`.

```sql
SELECT COUNT(*) AS remaining
FROM idea_tasks
WHERE project_id = '<project_id>' AND is_complete = false;

-- If remaining = 0:
UPDATE idea_projects SET status = 'review' WHERE id = '<project_id>';
INSERT INTO idea_comments (project_id, body, type)
VALUES ('<project_id>', 'All tasks complete. Moved project to Review.', 'system');
```

## Important Notes

- **Subtask depth**: Only one level of nesting is allowed. A subtask cannot have its own subtasks (enforced by database trigger).
- **Status flow**: idea -> planned -> in_progress -> review -> done (or archived at any point).
- **Priority values**: low, medium, high, urgent.
- **Comment types**: `comment` (human), `status_change` (auto-logged), `system` (agent/automation).
- Use `type = 'system'` when agents add comments so they are distinguishable from human comments.
